1 Intro

d3-jsEcharts(Github Repo)Yang ZhouTaiyun WeirechartsYihui XiehtmlwidgetsjsechartREchartR>=3.2.0.

This tool originates from a top-tier d3-js visualization project of China: Baidu Echarts(Github Repo). Yang Zhou and Taiyun Wei developed an experimental R package recharts based on it, which then evoluted into yihui/recharts by Yihui Xie to pass js parameters through htmlwidgets. The package is sill uder development. I developed a function echartR based on this package to make basic Echarts interation charts. This function requires R>=3.2.0.

echartREchartslistYihui Xieechartlistechart

echartR majorly packs Echarts parameters into a list while echart, the prototype function developed by Yihui Xie, is used to parse the list. The basic examples of echart is as follows, which does not provide parameters entries other than dataset itself.

if (! 'recharts' %in% installed.packages()[,1]){
    install.packages('recharts',
                     repos = c('http://yihui.name/xran', 'http://cran.rstudio.com')
                     )
}
library(recharts)
echart(iris, ~Sepal.Length, ~Sepal.Width)

echart(iris, ~Sepal.Length, ~Sepal.Width, series = ~Species)

echartR

2.1 Installation

  • Install devtools (install.packages('devtools'))
  • Insall recharts (install_github('yihui/recharts'))
  • Download echartR.R script file to local disk: https://github.com/madlogos/recharts/blob/master/R/echartR.R)
  • Source echartR script ( suppose I stored the script to local GitHub Repo: source("~/Github/recharts/R/echartR.R"))

2.2 Grammar 

echartR(data, x=NULL, y, z=NULL, series=NULL, weight=NULL, 
        xcoord=NULL, ycoord=NULL, x1=NULL, xcoord1=NULL, ycoord1=NULL, 
        type="scatter", stack=FALSE,
        title=NULL, subtitle=NULL, title_url=NULL, subtitle_url=NULL,
        symbolList=NULL, dataZoom=NULL, 
        dataRange=NULL, splitNumber=NULL, dataRangePalette=NULL,
        xAxis=list(lab=NULL,color=NULL,splitLine=T,banded=F,rotate=0), xlab=NULL,
        yAxis=list(lab=NULL,color=NULL,splitLine=T,banded=F,rotate=0), ylab=NULL,
        xAxis1=list(lab=NULL,series=NULL,reverse=F,color=NULL,splitLine=T,
                              banded=F,rotate=0), xlab1=NULL, 
                  yAxis1=list(lab=NULL,series=NULL,reverse=F,color=NULL,splitLine=T,
                              banded=F,rotate=0), ylab1=NULL,
        xyflip=FALSE, AxisAtZero=TRUE, scale=TRUE,
        palette='aetnagreen', tooltip=TRUE, legend=TRUE, toolbox=TRUE, 
        pos=list(title=6, legend=11, toolbox=1, dataZoom=6, dataRange=8, roam=2),
        calculable=TRUE, asImage=FALSE,
        markLine=NULL, markLinesmooth=NULL, markPoint=NULL, 
        theme=list(backgroundColor=NULL, borderColor=NULL,
                borderWidth=1),
        ...))
  • data: dataset
  • x: xx variable, only omitable for histograms, pie, ring and rose charts
  • y: y y variable
  • z: z/z variable, only accept data/time variable to open time axis
  • series: Series() series variable
  • weight: weight variable, used in histogram, bubble, etc
  • xcoord: /mapLattitude variable, only for point/line-marking map.
  • ycoord: /mapLongitude variable, only for point/line-marking map.
  • x1: Backup x variable, only for line-marking map, force andchord chart.
  • xcoord1: mapBackup lattitude variable, only for line-marking map.
  • ycoord1: mapBackup Longitude variable, only for line-marking map.
  • type: default scatter options scatter, bubble, bar, line, linesmooth, map, k, pie, ring, rose,area, areasmooth, chordribbon, chord, force, tree, treemap, wordcloud, heatmap, histogram, funnel, pyramid, radar, radarfill
    • map3c(map,mapType,markType)mapTypeworldchinamarkTypeareapointlinec(map,china,area)If map was chosen, the control option should be a vector of length 3: c(map,mapType,markType). mapType could be either world or china, of which simplified Chinese names are required for china. When markType equals to area, the function colors polygons to show the effects; while equals to point, it ticks pins on the map; while equals to line, it ticks lines on the map.
  • stack: FALSEDefault to FALSE (do not stack). Used in stacked column, bar, line and area chart, etc.
  • title: title of the figure
  • subtitle: subtitle of the figure
  • pos: 1-126111682Position of image elements which are integers 1-12. Title position default to 6 (oclock), which means bottom middle. Defaults to legend, toolbox, dataRange, dataZoom, roamController are 11, 1, 6, 8, 2, respectively.
  • title_url: url of the title
  • subtitle_url: , url of the subtitle
  • symbolList: seriesNULLEchartsc(circle,rectangle,triangle,diamond,emptyCircle,emptyRectangle,emptyTriangle,emptyDiamond)heart,droplet,pin,arrow,star5,star6noneA vector assigning symbols. You can use an array of symbols. If the length of the symbols array is smaller than number of levels of the series, the last symbol will be used to extend the array. If you set symbolList NULL or leave it unset, the function circulates the default symbol list of Echarts: c(circle,rectangle,triangle,diamond,emptyCircle,emptyRectangle,emptyTriangle,emptyDiamond). You can also assign non-standard symbols, such as heart,droplet,pin,arrow,star5,star6, star7, etc. When assigned to none, no symbols are shown.
  • dataZoom: FALSE. The axis to zoom data. Default to FALSE. dataZoom=TRUE0-100%2c(30,70)30-70%If dataZoom=TRUE, the default range is 0-100%. You can assign a vector with length of 2 to dataZoom to control the initial range. E.g.,c(30,70) means from 30% to 70% at the initial view.
  • dataRange: dataRange=c(,) The range to zoom the data. Default to FALSE. Set dataRange=c(High value label,Low value label) to enable dataRange.
  • splitNumber: (0)splitNumbersplitNumberWhen dataRange is on, assign splitNumber to cut the range into discrete sections. Default to 0 (continuous range). In histogram, if splitNumber is set, the y variable will be cut into splitNumber groups.
  • dataRangePalette: (palette)EchartsYou can independently assign palettes to dataRange (similar to overall palette). Default to NULL (applies echarts defaults).
  • xAxis: xlist(lab=NULL,color=NULL,splitLine=T,banded=F,rotate=0),labcolorsplitLinebandedrotate(-90 ~ 90)x Axis parameters in a list, default to list(lab=NULL,color=NULL,splitLine=T,banded=F,rotate=0).
  • yAxis: yxAxisparameters of y Axis. Refer to xAxis.
  • xlab: xAxisxlabxxAxis[['lab']]xlabxlabYou can also omit xAxis, directly assign xAxis title. xlab has a higher priority than xAxis[['lab']].
  • ylab: yAxisylabyyAxis[['lab']]ylabylabYou can also omit yAxis, directly assign yAxis title. ylab has a higher priority than yAxis[['lab']].
  • xAxis1: xlist(lab=NULL,series=NULL,reverse=F,color=NULL,splitLine=T,banded=F,rotate=0)seriesc(1,2)c(male,female)reverseTRUESecondary x axis, effecitve only if there are multiple series. Written in a list, default to list(lab=NULL,series=NULL,reverse=F,color=NULL,splitLine=T,banded=F,rotate=0). series set which series to put on secondary x-axis, which can be either a name vector or an index vector, e.g., c(1,2) or c(male,female). The data is fliped up when reverse is set TRUE.
  • yAxis1yxAxis1
  • xlab1xxAxis1labTitle of secondary x-axis, with higher priority than lab in xAxis1 list,
  • ylab1yyAxis1labTitle of secondary y-axis, with higher priority than lab in yAxis1 list,
  • xyflip: FALSEFlip x,y-axies. Default to FALSE.
  • AxisAtZero: FALSEAxes cross at zero. Default to FALSE.
  • scale: TRUERescale the axes based on min and max values. Default to TRUE.
  • palette: aetnagreenOverall palette. Default to aetnagreen.
    • Palette names:
      • Aetna palettes: Including aetnagreen, aetnablue, aetnaviolet, aetnaorange, aetnateal, aetnacranberry
      • RColorBrewer palettes: Including BrBG, PiYG, PRGn, PuOr, RdBu, RdGy, RdYlBu, RdYlGn, Spectral, Accent, Dark2, Paired, Pastel1, Pastel2, Set1, Set2, Set3, Blues, BuGn, BuPu, GnBu, Greens, Greys, Oranges, OrRd, PuBu, PuBuGn, PuRd, Purples, RdPu, Reds, YlGn, YlGnBu, YlOrBr, YlOrRd
      • ggthemes palettes: calc, economist, economist_white, economist_stata,excel, exel_fill, excel_old, excel_new, few, fivethirtyeight, gdocs, pander, tableau, stata, stata1,stata1r,statamono, tableau20, tableau10medium, tableaugray, tableauprgy, tableaublrd, tableaugnor, tableaucyclic, tableau10light, tableaublrd12, tableauprgy12, tableaugnor12,hc,darkunica, solarized,solarized_red, solarized_yellow, solarized_orange,solarized_magenta,solarized_violet, solarized_blue, solarized_cyan, solarized_green, wsj, wsj_rgby, wsj_red_green, wsj_black_green, wsj_dem_rep, colorblind, trafficlight
      • Other palettes: rainbow, terrain, topo, heat, cm
    • Usage:
      • Do not set the value and function defaults will be loaded
      • palette=NULLEchartsSet palette=NULL to use Echarts defaults
      • palette=palette nameSet palette=palette name to assign any palette listed above
      • palette='calc(3)'calc3Set palette=palette name(number) to restrict number of colors within the palette (e.g., palette='calc(3)' picks 3 colors out of calc RANDOMLY)
      • palette=c(color1,color2,color3,...)Hexcolors()demo(colors)Set palette=c(color1,color2,color3,...) to define a palette vector, made of which either color names or Hex expressions. Use colors() to check available color names and check the effects using demo(colors).
  • tooltip: TRUEMouse tip effects swtich. Default to TRUE.
  • legend: TRUE2list(mode='single/multiple',select=)list(mode='single',select='Male')Malelegend=FALSEWhether to show the legend. Default to TRUE. Can also be a list length 2: list(mode='single/multiple',select=vector(...)). E.g., list(mode='single',select='Male') means singular choice, with series Male selected at the initial view. legend=FALSE closes legend.
  • toolbox: TRUEEcharts Tool box switch. Default to TRUE.
  • calculable: TRUE(Echarts) Calculable switch (Echarts patent).
  • asImage: FALSErenderAsImage switch.Deafult to FALSE.
  • markLine: 48 Show markline, default to NULL. The grammar is a data.frame or matrix with 4 or 8 columns:
    • Short form
    series name/index * line name Line type Light effect
    String or number String / NA min/max/average/lm TRUE / FALSE
    • Full form :
    series name/index * line name Value P0 x P0 y P1 x P1 y Light effect
    String or number String/NA num x val y val x val y val TRUE / FALSE
    • Examples
    1. t(c('male',NA,'average',F))t(c(1,NA,'average',F))maleline, linesmooth, bar, scatter, bubblelmt(c(1,NA,'average',T))maleE.g., both t(c('male',NA,'average',F)) and t(c(1,NA,'average',F)) refer to an average markline of the series male, only available for line, linesmooth, bar, scatter, bubble charts. lm refers to linear regresson markline which is only available for scatters and bubbles. t(c(1,NA,'average',T)) opens light effects of series male.
    2. t(c('male',NA,100,0,5,100,5,F))maleP0(0,5)P1(100,5)E.g., t(c('male',NA,100,0,5,100,5,F)) refers to a markline through P0(0,5) and P1(100,5) as of sereis male. line, bar, k, scatterP0 x,P0 y,P1 x,P1 ymap t(c('male',NA,100,0,5,100,5,T))male In line, bar, k and scatter charts, P0 x,P0 y,P1 x,P1 y are comprehended as coordinates. In map charts, these coordinates should be lattitudes and longitudes. t(c('male',NA,100,0,5,100,5,T)) opens light effects of series male.
  • markLinesmooth: markLinesmoothmarkLineUsed this instead of markLine for smooth marklines with totally identical grammar.
  • markPoint: 46 Show markpoints, default to NULL. The grammar is a data.frame or matrix with 4 or 6 columns:
    • Short form
    series name/index * Point name Point type Light effect
    String or number String / NA min/max TRUE / FALSE
    • Full form :
    series name/index * Point name Value P x P y Light effect
    String or number String / NA num x val y val TRUE / FALSE
    • Examples
    1. t(c('male',NA,'min',F))t(c(1,NA,'min',F))maleline, linesmooth, bar, scatter, bubblet('male',NA,'min',T)maleE.g., both t(c('male',NA,'min',F)) and t(c(1,NA,'min',F)) refer to a min markpoint of the series male, only available for line, linesmooth, bar, scatter, bubble charts. t(c('male',NA,'min',T)) opens light effects of series male.
    2. t(c('male',NA,100,0,5,F))maleP(0,5)E.g., t(c('male',NA,100,0,5,F)) refers to a markpoint at P(0,5) as of sereis male. line, bar, k, scatterP x,P y, map t(c('male',NA,100,0,5,T))male In line, bar, k and scatter charts, P x,P y, are comprehended as coordinates. In map charts, these coordinates should be lattitudes and longitudes. t(c('male',NA,100,0,5,T)) opens light effects of series male.
  • theme: theme=list(backgroundColor=color name/value, borderColor=color name/value, borderWidth=1)colorNULLwidth1

3.1 Scatter

3.1.1 Mono-series Scatter

1(markLine=c(1,NA,'average',F))

echartR(data = iris, x = ~Sepal.Width, y = ~Petal.Width, 
        type = 'scatter', palette='solarized_magenta',
        title = 'Scatter - Sepal Width vs Petal Width', 
        subtitle = "(source: iris)", xlab = 'Sepal Width', ylab = 'Petal Width',
        markLine=t(c(1,'Mean',"average",F)))

        type = 'scatter', palette='wsj_dem_rep', symbolList='circle',

        subtitle ='(source: iris)', 
        markLine=rbind(c(2,'Mean','average',F),c('versicolor','Maximum','max',F),
                       c(2,'Minimum','min',F)),
        markPoint=rbind(c(1,'Max','max',F),c(2,'Min','min',F), c(3,'Max','max',T)))

for (i in 1:2001)  e <- c(e,rnorm(1,0,x[i]+abs(min(x))))

3.2.2 Multi-series Bubble

symbolList=c('circle','emptyCircle')1palettetableauGnOr(3)3

(lm())echartRSepal WidthPetal Width

fit <- lm(Petal.Width~Sepal.Width,iris)
pred <- data.frame(Sepal.Width=c(min(iris$Sepal.Width),max(iris$Sepal.Width)))
yhat <- round(predict(fit,pred),2)
echartR(data = iris, x = ~Sepal.Width, y = ~Petal.Width, 
        weight = ~Petal.Length, series = ~Species, 
        symbolList=c('emptyCircle','circle'), 
        type = 'bubble', palette='tableaugnor(4)',
        title = paste('Bubble - Sepal Width vs Petal Width, by Species,',
                      'weighed by Petal Length'), 
        subtitle = '(source: iris)', xlab = 'Sepal Width', ylab = 'Petal Width',
        markLine=t(c('Reg Coef.','slope',round(fit$coefficients[[2]],2), 
                     pred[1,1],yhat[[1]],pred[2,1],yhat[[2]],F)))
